   {:e #blake3 "a1e2940d078eb43c51bd4b2e63d33dbbd90c0d1144cc6604e25ae13def10bdb7" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "COMPILE-TO-PROMPT — VERIFICATION AND COMPOUNDING: Verification: (1) Property: for any task T with spec refs R(T), every invariant in compile_constraints(S,T) has a path from some r in R(T) through :spec/traces-to edges — no irrelevant constraints leak in. (2) Density test: compile_seed achieves higher semantic density (relevant tokens / total tokens) than assemble_seed for the same budget. (3) Demonstration quality: tasks with demonstrations produce output that structurally matches the demonstration more closely than tasks without. Compounding: every closed task adds to the demonstration corpus. After 100 sessions: seed knows which formal systems each namespace needs, has 500+ examples. After 1000 closed tasks: the compiler covers most task archetypes. Risks: overfitting to task description (mitigated by C1-C7 floor), demonstration staleness (mitigated by recency weighting). Interaction: TSV format helps compile_demonstrations because it can efficiently query the closed task corpus.; COMPILE-TO-PROMPT — IMPLEMENTATION DESIGN: Four compilation phases in seed.rs. (1) compile_priors(store, task) -> String: analyze task spec refs, determine which formal systems are needed (spectral theory, falsification, lattice, type theory), emit 2-3 activation sentences. Uses namespace→formal-system mapping stored as :prior/* datoms. ~100 tokens. (2) compile_constraints(store, task) -> Vec<String>: follow task spec refs through :spec/traces-to edges, collect transitive closure of invariants, select top 5 by Jaccard similarity of keywords between task title and invariant statement. ~200 tokens. (3) compile_demonstrations(store, task) -> Option<String>: find closed task with highest structural similarity (same FILE: markers, same spec namespace, same task type). Format its title + completion reason as a worked example. Weight by recency (exponential decay, half-life 10 sessions). ~300 tokens. (4) compile_directives(store, task) -> String: task title with acceptance criteria extracted and formatted as verification checklist. ~200 tokens. Total: ~1000 tokens compiled seed vs ~2000 tokens retrieved seed = 2x density improvement.; REFLEXIVE DIVERGENCE: The output pipeline has a 4th consumer that the 3-mode model doesn't account for: the agent-as-tool-user. When I (the LLM agent) call braid task list --format json and pipe through Python to extract specific fields, I'm performing a projection that braid already knows how to compute. The JSON mode is a serialization format, not an output mode — it's an intermediate representation that requires a second language runtime to decode. TSV would eliminate this by making the projection a first-class output concern. But the deeper insight is: the output pipeline should support PROJECTIONS, not just MODES. A mode is a fixed rendering strategy. A projection is a parameterized extraction: which fields, in what order, with what separator. The current 3-mode system maps to 3 fixed projections: {all fields as JSON}, {context+content+footer}, {formatted table}. TSV adds a 4th. But the algebraic structure that unifies all 4 is: Projection(fields: Vec<Field>, separator: char, header: bool). This is the free object over the field algebra.; TSV-COMPILE INTERACTION: The two EPICs are synergistic, not independent. TSV enables efficient self-querying for the compile-to-prompt system. compile_demonstrations needs to search 400+ closed tasks by structural similarity — with TSV it can do: braid task list --all --format tsv | grep closed | sort by spec-namespace. Without TSV it needs the 15-line Python pipeline. More broadly: TSV is the machine-to-machine interface that makes braid composable with itself. The compile-to-prompt system is the first major consumer of that composability. INV-SEED-001 (seed as store projection) + INV-BUDGET-006 (density monotonicity) + INV-INTERFACE-001 (output modes) form the spec triangle governing both EPICs.; Session entity: :task/t-74998cc6; Session entity: :task/t-93f95bbc; Session entity: :task/t-37a15b73; TSV IMPLEMENTATION DESIGN — The change touches output.rs (add Tsv variant to OutputMode enum), main.rs (add 'tsv' to parser, bypass budget gate for TSV like JSON), and each command module that produces structured data. Per-command field specifications: task list → id,priority,type,status,title (5 fields). task ready → id,priority,impact,title (4 fields). status → key,value pairs (2 fields, one row per metric). query → entity,attribute,value (3 fields). witness status → inv_id,status,depth,alignment (4 fields). topology plan → agent,tasks,files,impact (4 fields). Each command adds a tsv: String field to its CommandOutput, populated alongside json/agent/human. Header row uses field names. No --fields flag initially (fixed per command). TSV bypasses budget gate (consumer controls own budget). CommandOutput::render(Tsv) returns the tsv field. The spec change is INV-INTERFACE-001: 'three modes' becomes 'four modes'.; TSV OUTPUT FORMAT — PROBLEM: Every braid CLI invocation that produces structured data (task list, query, status) forces the LLM consumer through a JSON→Python→extraction pipeline costing ~500 tokens and ~15 lines per invocation. This is a reflexive divergence (INV-REFLEXIVE-001): braid knows the field structure, the consumer knows what fields it wants, but JSON is an intermediate representation requiring a second runtime to decode. The current 3-mode OutputMode (Json|Agent|Human) treats output as fixed renderings. But the consumer needs PROJECTIONS — parameterized field extractions. TSV is the minimal projection: fields separated by tabs, one entity per line, header row. Universally parseable by awk/cut/sort/head with zero dependencies. Density improvement: ~4 tokens/task (TSV) vs ~15 tokens/task (JSON) = 3.75x. This directly serves INV-BUDGET-006 (density monotonicity) and closes the reflexive divergence where the system's output format mismatches the consumer's consumption format.\nSession entity: :task/t-2b19c059; Session entity: :task/t-c8f7f66a; Session entity: :task/t-be34dcd5; Session entity: :task/t-29c9f672; Session entity: :task/t-b027b6df; Session entity: :task/t-9e5efb1f; Session entity: :task/t-f5300190; Session entity: :task/t-b696e576; Session entity: :task/t-3a498622; Session entity: :task/t-ef2b25b6" :op :assert}
